[4] India (Delhi)
Date: Sun 14 Oct 2007
Source: The Economic Times [edited]
<http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/PoliticsNation/First_case_of_Dengue_death_in_Delhi/articleshow/2456766.cms>


The 1st dengue death of the Capital was reported on Saturday [13 Oct
2007] as a 22-year-old man succumbed to the disease at Maharaja
Agrasen Hospital in Punjabi Bagh. He was a resident of Narela. This
is the 1st dengue death to be reported this year [2007] from the
Capital,'' said MCD (Municipal Corporation of Delhi) health officer N
K Yadav.

Yadav said this year [2007], the number of cases being reported are
much less than what had been reported by this time last year: in
2006, the 1st dengue death had occurred as early as 19 Aug at AIIMS
(All India Institute of Medical Sciences). By 14 Oct, 28 dengue
deaths had been reported in the Capital. This number steadily rose to
42 by 20 Oct, which by the end of the month, had further risen to 58.

''On an average, 8-15 cases come in everyday. This is still
negligible compared to the number of cases that were reported last
year [2006] during this time. The total number of dengue cases
reported so far is 197,'' added Yadav.

While 8 new dengue cases were reported on Saturday [13 Oct 2007],
last year [2006] on 13 Oct, 77 fresh cases had been reported. In
2006, by this day [14 Oct], a total of 843 new cases of dengue had
been reported, more than 4 times [that] of the 197 reported this year
[2007].

Avoiding water from accumulating and keeping water meant for storage
covered are the best precautions as even a cap full can provide
breeding ground for as many as 250 eggs. Using mosquito repellents
and creams and wearing full-sleeved clothes can go a long way in
preventing the disease.

--
