[6] Worldwide
Date: Wed 10 Oct 2007
Source: Center for Infectious Disease Research & Policy (CIDRAP) [edited]
<http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/bt/vhf/news/oct1107dengue.html>


Global health officials have noted sharp rises in the number of
dengue fever cases in recent months, particularly in Latin American,
Caribbean, and Asian countries where the disease is endemic.

A recent surveillance update from the World Health Organization's
(WHO's) Southeast Asia office in New Delhi reported that Thailand has
more than 40 000 cases so far this year [2007], reflecting a 27
percent increase over 2006, Deutsche Presse Agentur (DPA) reported on
9 Oct [2007]. Indonesia's total of 100 000 cases represents a 10
percent increase over last year [2006], and Myanmar has reported
almost 12 000 cases -- a third more than it reported in 2006.

The Pan American Health Organization (PAHO), which tracks and manages
health issues for the WHO in Latin American and Caribbean countries,
reported on 4 Oct [2007] that the disease is reaching epidemic levels
in some of the locations it monitors. In a statement released to
journalists, the organization said it has recorded 630 356 cases so
far this year [2007], an 11 percent increase from 2006. Of this
year's [2007] cases, 12 147 were the more severe dengue hemorrhagic
fever (DHF), and 183 cases were fatal.

Jarbas Barbosa da Silva, PAHO's manager of health surveillance and
disease management, said in the press release that all 4 dengue
[virus] serotypes were in circulation [in Latin America], "which
increases the risk for appearance of the most serious forms of the
disease -- namely, dengue hemorrhagic fever and dengue shock
syndrome."

For the 1st time, Paraguay has reported cases of hemorrhagic fever
and deaths from the disease this year [2007], Barbosa da Silva said.
Southernmost Latin American countries have accounted for 60 percent
of the region's dengue cases, with Brazil reporting the most, the
PAHO report said. The Andean region has had 19 percent of the cases,
with Colombia and Venezuela reporting the highest numbers. Other
countries reporting high rates are French Guiana, Martinique, Costa
Rica, and Honduras.

PAHO's report says Mexico has reported 67 563 dengue cases, of which
5212 involved hemorrhagic fever. Health officials in Nuevo Laredo,
Mexico, on the US border, recently reported 71 pending or confirmed
dengue fever cases, according to a 9 Oct [2007] report in the Laredo
Morning Times.

A recent [10 Aug 2007] article in the CDC's (US Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention) Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (MMWR)
[<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5631a1.htm>] said that
dengue fever is gaining a stronger foothold in southern Texas [in
2005]. The report documented the 1st DHF case in a Texas resident
native to the Texas-Mexico border area and found that 38 percent of
surveyed Brownsville, Texas, residents had IgG antibodies to dengue,
indicating that a substantial proportion of the city population had
been infected with the virus.

Puerto Rico's health department is recording 500 cases a week, with a
cumulative of 6175 cases and 4 deaths this year [2007], according to
a Reuters report. Local press reports in the Dominican Republic say
the country has logged 6000 cases and 30 deaths.

PAHO noted that one contributing factor is waste tires and dumps
filled with discarded plastic that create potential breeding sites
for mosquitoes.

In July [2007], the WHO's Western Pacific regional office in Manila
warned countries in the area that a major dengue outbreak could occur
unless they quickly undertook coordinated efforts to curb the spread
of the disease. The WHO said the disease had arrived earlier than
usual, but it was difficult to estimate the magnitude of the outbreak
because official information from most of the counties was incomplete.

John Ehrenberg, a WHO regional adviser, said several factors were
contributing to the spread of dengue: population explosion,
migration, and rapid urban growth, all of which strain public health
services and access to clean water.

"People exposed to these settings often rely on containers to collect
water for their own drinking supply. These containers can become
mosquito-breeding sites," he said. "Water storage practices are
therefore a key target of dengue prevention and control programs."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Unfortunately, the PAHO country reports are an underestimate of the
actual numbers of cases. Only 3 countries -- El Salvador, Honduras,
and Nicaragua -- are current in their reporting. Some are more than 8
months behind. Since dengue viruses are not limited by international
borders, it is important that regional reporting of dengue cases,
preferably by dengue virus serotype, be timely and accurate. -
Mods.JW/TY]

The WHO (World Health Organization) description of dengue fever and
the more deadly dengue hemorrhagic fever [DHF] can be found in
ProMED-mail's "Dengue/DHF update 20070514.1541". ProMED-mail thanks
the contributors to this update and encourages others to contribute
reports also. - Mod.TY]
